The paper focuses on the design of a very efficient massive access strategy for highly dense cellular networks with M2M communications, which involves the use of coding and modulation techniques to allow multiple devices to transmit simultaneously in the same resource block. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Networking and Internet Architecture (cs.NI) sub-category. Additionally, the paper discusses the use of Raptor codes, which are a type of fountain code used for efficient transmission of data over unreliable channels, and the analysis of the maximum number of MTC devices that can be supported in a resource block, which suggests that the paper may also belong to the Information Theory (cs.IT) sub-category. The paper also discusses the use of a random access strategy and the estimation of the number of devices that have chosen certain preambles, which suggests that the paper may belong to the Systems and Control (cs.SY) sub-category. Finally, the paper discusses the use of modulation schemes and the improvement of system throughput, which suggests that the paper may also belong to the Multimedia (cs.MM) and Cryptography and Security (cs.CR) sub-categories.
